<HL> Cyprus Minerals Says
It Earned $4 Million
In The Fourth Quarter</HL>
<DD> 01/22/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CYPM
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO) </IN>
<DATELINE> DENVER  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyprus Minerals Co. expects to report fourth-quarter earnings of about $4 million, or 15 cents a share, on revenue of about $200 million, Kenneth J. Barr, president and chief executive officer, said. 

   For the year-earlier fourth quarter, the mining company reported a loss of $415.8 million on revenue of $218.7 million. 
The loss included a charge of $432.5 million from a write-down of assets. 

   For the year, Cyprus will report earnings of $19 million to $20 million, or 75 cents to 80 cents a share, on revenue of about $800 million, Mr. Barr said in an interview. 
For 1985, the company reported a loss of $452.1 million, including the fourth-quarter charge, on revenue of $706 million. 

   The company, which mines coal, industrial minerals and metals, has "recovered nicely" from several financial blows since it was spun off by Amoco Corp. in July 1985, the executive said. 
The setbacks included the cancellation of its major metallurgical coal contract by LTV Corp., which filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code in July 1986, and declines in prices and demand for industrial minerals, coal and metal, he said. 

   Contributing to the mining company's move to profitability in 1986 were the acquisition of the Sierrita copper and molybdenum mine in Arizona at the end of the first quarter, cost reductions at its Thompson Creek molybdenum mine in Montana and the company's success at setting a floor under its molybdenum price despite industry overcapacity, Mr. Barr said. 

</TEXT>
