<HL> Amax Inc. Posts Widened Loss For Fourth Period </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> AMX </CO>
<IN> ERN MIN </IN>
<DATELINE> GREENWICH, Conn.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amax Inc. reported a loss of $280.8 million for the fourth quarter after large write-downs to restructure its molybdenum business. 

   The minerals and energy concern had a loss of $49.7 million in the year-earlier quarter. 

   Allen Born, president and chief executive officer, said the restructuring should allow the molybdenum business, which has been unprofitable in recent years, to break even in 1988. 

   The write-downs include the closing of the company's Kitsault mine in Prince Rupert, British Columbia, and the closing of underground operations at its Climax mine in Climax, Colo. 

   The company also announced that it formed an operating unit, Climax Metals Co., to consolidate its molybdenum and tungsten buinesses. 

   For the full year, Amax earned $51.2 million, or 53 cents a share, up sharply from the $14.3 million, or five cents a share, earned in 1986. 

   In addition to the large molybdenum write-downs, the 1987 results include a $6 million write-down of some domestic oil and gas properties and gains of $279.1 million from the sale of the concern's 47% stake in Australian Consolidated Minerals Ltd., a gold mine operator; $43.9 million from an overfunded pension plan, and $38.3 million from the sale of oil and gas properties in the Dutch North Sea. 

   The 1986 results included a charge of $80.9 million for discontinued operations and a gain of $80.1 million from an overfunded pension plan. 

   Amax shares closed Friday at $16.25, up 37.5 cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. 

