<LP>
   Copper producer Cyprus Minerals Corp. reported
fourth-quarter earnings dropped to 12 cents a share from 88
cents a share a year earlier, primarily because of a $40
million after-tax write-down on a molybdenum mine.
   In contrast, Magma Copper Co. said its fourth-quarter
earnings more than tripled to 49 cents a fully diluted share
from 14 cents a share as productivity improved and production
costs declined.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cyprus said in Denver that it earned $8.4 million on
revenue of $478.5 million, compared with $37.4 million on
revenue of $437.3 million in the 1989 fourth quarter. For the
year, the company reported earnings of $111 million, or $2.38
a share, after asset write-downs on coal, copper, molybdenum,
silver and beryllium facilities totaling about $63 million
after taxes. Revenue was $1.87 billion. In 1989, Cyprus
earned $164.9 million, or $3.87 a share, on revenue of $1.79
billion. Results for 1989 have been restated for a
tax-accounting change.
   Cyprus said fourth-quarter operating earnings rose in its
copper-gold-molydbenum group and its coal operations as
higher copper prices helped offset increased production
costs. Molybdenum prices and demand, however, declined
significantly, leading the company to decide to mothball its
Tonopah, Nev., mine this month.
   Magma, based in Tucson, Ariz., reported net income of
$20.4 million on sales of $178 million, compared with
earnings of $5.9 million on sales of $190 million. Copper
sales declined, but prices increased slightly in the quarter.
Productivity rose as the company's copper smelter reached
capacity and production costs were cut, in part by increasing
the amount of copper refined by energy-saving solvent
extraction methods.
   For the year, the company had net of $84.4 million, or
$2.02 a fully diluted share, up 44% from 1989 earnings of
$58.5 million, or $1.43 a share. Sales rose 18% to $767.3
million from $650 million. During the year, the company
increased its cash to $133.6 million from $49.4 million while
paying off bank debt of $37.5 million and spending $20.7
million to buy mining property in Nevada.
