<TEXT>
    Amax Inc. estimated that its
fourth-quarter net loss narrowed to $49.7 million from a $103
million loss a year earlier.
   For all of 1986, the metals and minerals concern said it had net income of $14.3 million, the company's first full-year profit since 1981, including a gain of $110 million related to pension-plan accounting changes. 
Amax said its "modest" 1986 profit is equivalent to five cents a share after preferred dividends. 

   In 1985, Amax had a full-year loss of $621 million, which included a provision of $360 million for losses on properties and investments. 

   The company didn't give any sales figures. 

   Allen Born, president and chief executive officer, told analysts in London, "We've stopped the bleeding." 
Mr. Born attributed the 1986 profit in part to Amax's disposal of "non-core businesses" such as iron ore, lead, copper mining and refining, nickel and most of the agricultural-chemical business. 

   The company's core businesses are aluminum, coal, gold and molybdenum. 
"We're now concentrating our resources and technology in businesses where Amax has relatively low production costs and sustainable competitive advantages," Mr. Born said. 

   Mr. Born said that in addition to generating $450 million in cash from asset sales, the company has trimmed corporate costs, lowered interest expense and reduced the work force. 

   The estimate of the most recent fourth-quarter loss includes a charge of $45 million for a reduction in the book value of the El Mochito mine in Honduras and a $44 million tax benefit from the elimination of some taxes that had been anticipated. 

