<HL> Cyprus Set to Pay
About $90 Million
For Foote Mineral
---
By Marj Charlier
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 12/16/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CYPM FTE NEM
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Cyprus Minerals Co. said it has agreed in principle to buy Foote Mineral Co. for about $90 million. 

   Foote is 82%-owned by Newmont Mining Corp., which has said it would seek to sell some businesses to reduce the huge debt incurred in its successful effort to squelch a takeover bid by Ivanhoe Partners, an investment group led by T. Boone Pickens. 
The sale of Foote would be Newmont's first sale under that plan, although the company has also said it is considering selling its 75% stake in Newmont Australia Ltd., a gold mining concern. 

   The Foote sale, however, will make only a small dent in Newmont's $2.1 billion long-term debt. 
The company borrowed about $2.1 billion in September to pay a $33 a share special dividend to stockholders. 
Mr. Pickens then dropped his bid for Newmont, but still holds about a 10% stake. 

   For Cyprus, on the other hand, the deal represents a new ingredient in its minerals production mix. 
Foote, based in Exton, Pa., produces lithium carbonate, which is used as an alloy in aluminum, as an ingredient in lubricants and in the manufacture of batteries. 
Most of the metals and minerals Cyprus produces are subject to cyclical price swings, but lithium has had very few price decreases in the past two decades, and demand for the metal is growing. 

   Currently, Denver-based Cyprus mines gold, molybdenum, copper, coal and a number of industrial minerals. 

   In the past six months, Foote has restructured its business, selling and closing its ferro-alloy facilities and its hard-rock lithium production facilities, leaving only the operations that produce lithium from brine. 

   In 1986, Foote had a loss of $8.1 million on revenue of $106 million. 
However, its lithium division earned $6.2 million before taxes on sales of $42 million. 
In 1986, Cyprus earned $21.1 million, or 81 cents a share, on revenue of $815 million, including an extraordinary charge of $13 million. 

   Under terms of the proposed acquisition, Cyprus would pay about $10.32 a share for Foote's 7.3 million common shares outstanding. 
Preferred stock holders will receive cash equal to 3.5 times the amount paid for common stock, Cyprus said. 
There are 396,454 preferred shares outstanding. 

   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Cyprus closed at $22.75 a share, up 12.5 cents. 
Foote rose $2.75 a share to close at $8.50 on the American Stock Exchange. 
Newmont closed at $35.50 a share, down $2.625 on the New York Stock Exchange. 

   Cyprus said it would use its current lines of credit to purchase the lithium producer. 
The company said it would merge Foote with an newly formed Cyprus unit. 
The acquisition is subject to approvals by the boards of Newmont and Foote and shareholders of Foote. 

</TEXT>
