<TEXT>
   Inspiration Resources Corp. said it signed a letter of intent to sell its U.S. copper producing and smelting unit for $125 million to Cyprus Mineral Co., Englewood, Colo. 

   Inspiration's move follows the action of other nonferrous metal producers in recent years to leave the copper business because prices until recently had been so depressed. 
It also signals the company's intent to sharply reduce its bank debt and concentrate more on distribution of agricultural chemicals, analysts said. 

   "It's a smart move for Inspiration's shareholders because it puts the company into a good position to reduce debt and recognize profit on other assets," said Daniel A. Roling, senior mining analyst for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.'s Capital Markets unit. 

   Mr. Roling noted that Inspiration is one of the biggest U.S. agricultural products distributors, with more than 250 retail operations of its Terra International unit in the Midwest, South and Southeast. 

   Reuben F. Richards, Inspiration chairman, said the sale would reduce the company's debt to less than 28% of capitalization from 42% at the end of 1987. 
James Simon, Inspiration's director of corporate affairs, said the sale would provide a after-tax gain of $45 million to $50 million in the third quarter. 
The sale is subject to a final agreement and regulatory approvals by July 1. 

   In the 1987 third quarter, Inspiration Resources earned $8.4 million, or 12 cents a share, on revenue of $235 million. 

   In Denver, a Cyprus spokesman said the purchase will make it the nation's second-largest copper producer, giving it total annual production of more than 525 million pounds a year. 
It also will give Cyprus its first smelter and rod plant, allowing it to better control its copper costs. 

   The minerals concern recently has sold or agreed to sell portions of its industrial minerals unit for a total of $125 million so that it can concentrate on copper, molybdenum and gold. 

   Inspiration Consolidated Copper Co., the subsidiary, employs about 980 people. 
In addition to the smelter, and rod plant, the unit has pit mines, a dump leaching operation, two concentrators, an acid plant, and a tankhouse in Claypool, Ariz. 
In 1987, it produced 105.6 million pounds of refined copper, or more than 53% of Inspiration Resources' total refined copper output. 

   If the sale is completed, Inspiration Resources would retain its Hudson Bay Mining &amp; Smelting unit in Canada, which mines copper and other metals. 
Cyprus has been a major supplier of copper concentrates to Inspiration's smelter, Inspiration said. 

   Metals analyst Mr. Roling said Inspiration's departure from the U.S. copper-producing business would leave Phelps Dodge Corp., Phoenix, Ariz.; Asarco Inc.; BP America Inc.'s BP Minerals America unit, formerly Kennocott Copper Corp.; and Magma Copper Co., San Manuel, Ariz., as major U.S. copper producers. 
In March 1987, Newmont Mining Corp. spun off 85% of the stock of Magma Copper to Newmont shareholders, retaining 15% ownership. 

   Mr. Roling said the average price of copper rose to 76 cents a pound last year from 60 cents in 1986 and 61 cents in 1985. 
Last December, copper was selling for as much as $1.46 a pound, but has since dropped to less than $1 a pound. 

   Inspiration's Mr. Simon noted that at the end of the first quarter, the company had long-term debt of $242.5 million with $84.6 million in current debt. 
"Our aim in this sale is to reduce our exposure to base metals and single commodities and strengthen our balance sheet," he said. 
"Then we can focus on extending our expertise in manufacturing and distribution in other areas." 

   (Revised WSJ May 31, 1988)
