<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amax Inc. announced plans Wednesday to
acquire Falconbridge Ltd. of Canada for $2.4 billion in cash,
capping a complete financial turnaround for the worldwide mining
company.
   If approved by shareholders, the deal will expand Amax's mining
operations and mark its return to nickel production. Toronto-based
Falconbridge is the world's second-largest nickel producer.
   Amax, the nation's third-largest coal and aluminum producer,
said it has secured financing needed to pay $2.8 billion, or
$36.12{ a share, in Canadian currency for Falconbridge.
   The offer is worth about $2.4 billion, or $30.50, in U.S.
dollars, an Amax spokeswoman said. The acquisition is subject to
approval by Canadian regulatory authorities.
   ``Falconbridge is an excellent organization with quality people
and assets. Its acquisition will complement Amax's current metals
businesses and position the company well to serve growing
markets,'' said Allen Born, Amax's chairman, chief executive and
president.
   Amax earned $741 million on revenue of $4.2 billion in 1988. In
the first six months of this year, the company reported $245.1
million in profits on revenue of $2.06 billion.
   Amax shares closed up 12{ cents Wednesday at $25.50 in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. Trading in
Falconridge shares was delayed until after the Amax announcement.
The stock shot up after it began trading, closing at $36.62{, up
$6.37{, on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
   In the last year, Amax sought to expand operations and Born said
it was interested in acquiring natural gas properties.
   The possibility of expansion seemed unlikely in 1985, when Amax
ended four years with $1.7 billion in losses.
   In addition to ill-advised ventures into silver and energy, Amax
rejected lucrative takeover offers from Standard Oil of California,
now Chevron Corp. Its interest payments on debts totaled $200
million a year.
   Born was hired in 1985 from a Canadian mining company to help
turn the company. Amax then sold about half the subsidiaries
contributing to its 1984 losses, pulling out of iron ore, nickel
and agricultural chemicals production. The work force was cut to
nearly half its 1981 peak of 20,385 workers.
   In 1986, Amax began making new acquisitions, particularly in
coal and aluminum. The combination of cuts and purchases returned
Amax to profitability in 1987 and its work force has grown again to
about 20,000 worldwide.
   Falconbridge is an international resource corporation that
explores for, develops, mines, processes and markets metals and
minerals. Its major product is nickel, but it also mines
ferronickel, copper and zinc.
   Falconbridge has 9,500 employees with major operations in
Canada, Norway and the Dominican Republic.
   Amax, a supplier of metals and energy, has as its major products
aluminium, coal, gold and molybdenum.
   The Falconbridge deal is conditioned on acceptance of Amax's
offer by at least two-thirds of Falconbridge shareholders. No
deadline has been set for tendering the company's 79 million fully
diluted shares, the Amax spokeswoman said.
   If the deal goes through, Amax has agreed to make an additional
offer to acquire all untendered shares. Amax recently moved its
headquarters from Greenwich to New York, but maintains corporate
offices here.
   Falconbridge immediately implemented a shareholder rights plan
to defend against hostile offers. The measures would give existing
shareholders the right to purchase additional stock at a bargain
rate if another party acquires at least 15 percent of Falconbridge
stock.
   The so-called ``poison pill'' plan will expire in 120 days if
the deal is not approved by shareholders, Amax and Falconbridge
said in a joint statement.
   The Amax spokeswoman said the company abandoned the nickel
business because it was only a refiner and not a miner. She said
Falconbridge presented Amax with a ``quality position'' in which it
will both mine and refine nickel.
</TEXT>
