<LP>
   Most mining companies are expected to post lower earnings
for the second quarter, compared with the year-earlier
quarter, as a result of lower metals prices, higher costs,
geological problems and weather-related slowdowns.
   But many analysts expect some modest increases in prices
and an improvement in earnings for the third quarter,
compared with the second quarter, though year-to-year
comparisons are likely to remain negative.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For copper companies, sluggish molybdenum prices combined
with a 13.5% decline in average copper prices from the
year-earlier quarter to produce significantly lower earnings.
Demand for copper was weaker during the latest quarter,
generally as a result of the North American recession,
resulting in an average price of about $1.03 a pound,
compared with $1.19 a pound a year earlier. Prices slipped
below $1 for June, the lowest monthly average price since
August 1988, says John E. Gross, the West Nyack, N.Y.,
publisher of the Copper Journal.
   Problems with chemical-leaching processes at some
refineries as a result of wet and cool weather increased
costs at some copper companies, especially those with
electro-winning processes, analysts say.
   Peter Ingersoll at Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. estimates
Cyprus Minerals Corp. will report second-quarter net income
of less than 50 cents a share, compared with 56 cents a share
a year earlier. J. Clarence Morrison, an analyst at
Prudential Securities Inc., puts Magma Copper Co. at 25 cents
a share, compared with 56 cents a share a year earlier. The
two analysts estimate that Phelps Dodge Corp. will report
earnings of $1.85 a share to $2.05 a share, down from $3.30 a
share a year earlier.
   "Comparisons of year-to-year earnings will be very, very
difficult" for most companies until the fourth quarter, Mr.
Morrison predicts.
   Copper-producer Asarco Inc., the largest producer of zinc,
silver and lead in the U.S., also will feel the pinch of
lower prices for those minerals. Zinc prices dropped 39% from
last year to about 53 cents a pound in June, while lead
prices declined about 32% to an average for the quarter of
about 26 cents a pound. And silver prices declined to about
$4.13 an ounce for the quarter from about $5.01 an ounce a
year earlier. Asarco estimates that its earnings fall four
cents a share from each penny drop in lead and zinc prices
and 20 cents a share for each $1 drop in silver prices. As a
result, Mr. Morrison estimates Asarco will report net income
of 40 cents a share, compared with $1.21 a share a year
earlier.
   Analysts, however, see some signs now that copper prices
may have bottomed out for the year. Production problems
throughout the world, including a mine collapse in Zaire; a
strike at Chuquicamata, the largest mine of the Chilean
government-owned Codelco; and a rock burst at Codelco's El
Teniente are starting to balance out world supply and demand
for copper, says Mr. Morrison.
   Moreover, slightly higher prices early in July have given
some indication that the mining industry may have weathered
the worst of the recession. While shipments of building wire
have declined 16% for the year to date, compared with the
year-earlier period, orders increased in the second quarter,
says Mr. Morrison. Most economic trends that affect copper
companies, especially automotive and construction sales, have
begun to turn around. "Rebounding may be too strong a word,"
says Mr. Gross. "But many indicators are showing steady
improvement."
   The export market is providing additional support for
copper prices. Year-to-date exports of copper, especially to
the Pacific Rim countries, have risen 86% to 120,148 short
tons, compared with 64,500 short tons in the 1990 period,
says Mr. Gross. Exports to Japan more than doubled to 68,940
tons, while exports to Thailand rose a hundred-fold to 1,800
tons from 18 tons, he says.
   During the second quarter, a slightly lower average gold
price, $361 an ounce, compared with $366 a year earlier,
affected gold company performance somewhat. But, analysts
say, earnings declines will be larger than the price drop
might indicate, because year-earlier earnings reflected
forward sales put in place a couple of years ago when prices
were much higher. Recent hedging opportunities have been much
more modest. "Certainly, the first six months of this year
haven't been a favorable environment for aggressive foreign
sales," says John Phizackerley at Shearson. If current
strength does lead to a sustained rally, with gold prices
reaching $385 an ounce, producers will step up their forward
sales programs, he says.
   In addition, some cost increases, ore grade declines and
write-downs of old, uneconomical mines are eating into
earnings, says John Tumazos, analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette Securities Corp. Also, a number of companies have
brought new mines into production with capital costs much
higher than their older producing mines, he says.
   Mr. Tumazos and Mr. Phizackerley estimate second-quarter
earnings at Battle Mountain Gold Co. at four cents a share to
five cents a share, compared with nine cents a share a year
earlier. They expect Homestake Mining Co. to post a loss of
two cents a share, compared with net income of 38 cents a
share last year. Mr. Phizackerley puts Newmont Gold Corp.
earnings at 33 cents a share, down from 35 cents a share,
while Amax Gold Inc. is expected to post earnings of 11 cents
a share, up from a year-earlier loss of seven cents a share.
The year-earlier figure included a write-off of Amax Gold's
investment in Canamax Resources Inc.
   Coal companies similarly will post a decline in earnings
for the quarter. Utilities worked off inventories left over
from the mild winter, keeping spot prices soft. In addition,
geological problems at several mines combined to depress
earnings at Pittston Co., Westmoreland Coal Co. and Addington
Resources Inc., analysts say.
   Bucking the trend, Ashland Coal Inc. continued to expand
production, and will report higher earnings, analysts say.
Raphael Villagren at Shearson puts Ashland earnings at 52
cents a share, compared with 48 cents a share a year earlier,
and Addington earnings flat at 10 cents a share, compared
with a disappointing year-earlier quarter. He and Marc Cohen
at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. believe Pittston will report net
income of 27 cents a share, compared with 52 cents a share,
and Westmoreland will show a loss of 10 cents a share to 15
cents a share, compared with net income of 63 cents of share.
Mr. Villagren believes Nerco Inc. will report net income of
23 cents a share, down from 54 cents a share, while Mr. Cohen
estimates Nerco will earn 35 cents. But, Mr. Cohen says, his
Nerco estimate "may not be conservative enough."
   As the summer has warmed up, putting more demand on
utilities, spot prices have bottomed out and inventories are
in better balance, says Mr. Cohen. If this summer is hot,
coal prices may modestly increase through the third quarter,
he says.
