<HL>
   Phelps Dodge to Report Per-Share Net
   Of $4 for Fourth Quarter, $13 for Year
   ----
   By Marj Charlier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/21/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PD
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
</IN>
<LP>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. -- Phelps Dodge Corp. said it expects to
report fourth-quarter earnings of about $3 a share, in line
with analysts' projections.
   A year earlier, the mining concern had a loss of $4.03 a
share, including a charge of $6.62 a share, or $237 million
after taxes, for write-downs on nonproducing mines and
smelters.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Yearley, chairman, said in an interview that the
company expects 1990 earnings to total about $13 a share,
compared with $7.46 a share in 1989 and with analysts'
estimates for 1990 averaging $12.82 a share. Revenue for the
year just ended will be close to 1989 revenue of $2.7
billion, Mr. Yearley said.
   Operating earnings fell slightly in 1990 because of
increased costs and spot copper prices that averaged about
$1.19 a pound, compared with $1.25 for 1989. Copper averaged
$1.18 a pound in the fourth quarter, compared with $1.14 a
year earlier.
   Although the copper price slipped in 1990, it remained
higher than analysts and some industry officials expected, in
spite of the slowing U.S. economy. Mr. Yearley said that was
because less than 25% of world copper production is used in
the U.S. Some of Asia's developing countries are "booming,"
he said. In addition, the amount of copper used in U.S.
construction has increased, as homebuilders use more wire for
electrical, telephone and audio systems than in the past, he
said.
   While "we continue to be optimistic about copper prices
for the decade," Mr. Yearley said, "we're less sure about
1991." One major unknown, he said, is the impact of the 280
million pounds of copper a year that will be added to the
world's supplies by Chile's Escondido mine, which started
production two months ago.
   Mr. Yearley also said Phelps Dodge substantially increased
its copper ore reserves in 1990 by verifying reserves at its
Morenci Coronado deposit in Arizona and its La Candelaria
deposit in Chile. The company says there are about 400
million tons of 1.14% copper ore in the Chilean property and
about 150 million tons of 0.7% copper ore at the Coronado
deposit.
   The company also expanded the life of its Tyrone copper
mine in New Mexico by locating more ore. Phelps Dodge had
planned to close the mine in 1990 but now plans to operate it
through 1991.
   Capital spending rose to about $290 million in 1990 from
$217 million in 1989 and is expected to remain at $290
million this year. Phelps Dodge is expanding its exploration
efforts to include zinc, lead, nickel, gold, platinum, silver
and chromium deposits, among other minerals and precious
metals, Mr. Yearley said. "Our core business is copper, and
that isn't going to change," he said, "but we would love to
find diversification in base and precious metals. The company
operates two small gold mines now, one in Botswana and one in
Mexico, and is evaluating a joint venture project in Montana.
It also produces gold, silver and molybdenum as byproducts of
its copper output.
   Phelps Dodge's non-mining Industry Group continued to earn
about $100 million after tax last year, providing a stability
that levels out earnings swings resulting from changes in
copper commodity prices, Mr. Yearley said. "It earns our
dividend," he said. The company pays a regular dividend of $3
a year, or 75 cents a quarter.
   Although U.S. truck and construction industries slipped
into a recession in 1990, more than 50% of the group's
business is international and benefitted from healthier
overseas economies, he said. For instance, Mr. Yearley said,
infrastructure development in Asia contributed to a "banner
year" for the international cable companies that Phelps Dodge
holds an interest in. But he said he expects some "softness"
in the magnet wire business in 1991 because much of that
business depends on consumer appliance sales.
   Mr. Yearley said the company would like to add assets to
the Industry Group, which produces carbon black, truck wheels
and rims, and cables and magnet wires, and holds investments
in foreign mines and wire and cable manufacturers. But
recently, acquisition prices of target companies have been
too high, he said. The company rebuilt its cash by year end
to $150 million after significantly reducing cash through a
special dividend of $10 a share, or $352 million, it paid to
holders in 1989.
</TEXT>
