<HL>
   Recession Trims Mining Firms' Results
   ---
   Aluminum Concerns Are
   Hardest Hit During 4th Quarter
   ----
   By Marj Charlier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/07/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<CO>
   AA RLM AL MCU PD AR CYM ABX T.ABX BMG HM NGC ECO T.ECO NER
T.NER PCO WMOR
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
DIVERSIFIED MINING (MNG)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
ALUMINUM (ALU)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
COAL PRODUCERS (COA)
</IN>
<LP>
   The recession began to take its toll on many mining
companies' profits during the fourth quarter. The slowing
economy hit aluminum companies hardest, as declines in the
construction and automotive industries pushed prices down and
swelled inventories. Gold lost the boost it received in the
third-quarter from the Mideast situation, and silver prices
dipped nearly 10%.
   But copper prices held up surprisingly well in the face of
the recession, analysts say, leading a few to speculate that
the world's copper supply-and-demand balance has shifted
significantly and, changing their expectations for copper
prices in the future.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Alumina and aluminum-ingot prices fell. Although ingot
prices dipped only about 1.5 cents a pound from the year-ago
quarter to about 77 cents, the price had declined about 30
cents since September of 1990. Prices for can sheet and other
fabricated aluminum products softened even more as orders
slowed and inventories increased. Analysts expect further
softening through the first six to nine months of 1991.
   The decline in alumina prices affected Aluminum Co. of
America, which produces that raw material for aluminum as
well as aluminum ingots. On top of that, Alcoa said Friday
that it will take an after-tax charge of $275 million for
asset writedowns, environmental cleanup, and a loss on the
sale of its Astech division.
   "This is the third year in a row with disappointing
fourth-quarter results" for Alcoa, said J. Clarence Morrison
at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., who estimates the
company will show a $1.24 operating profit and a loss of
$1.94 for the quarter after the charge compared with a profit
of $1.88 a year ago. He estimated Alcoa averaged only 70 to
72 cents for the fourth quarter for its ingot sales,
primarily as a result of forward sales. Thomas Van Leeuwen at
Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. said he expects the company to
report fourth-quarter earnings of $1.40 before the charge.
   Mr. Van Leeuwen estimates Reynolds Metals Co. will show
$1.95 compared with $2.51 and Alcan Aluminium Ltd. will
report 40 cents compared with 60 cents. Alcan also is
expected to report a $160 million, or 70 cent per-share,
extraordinary gain from the sale of shares of Shin Nikkei Co.
to the public. R. Wayne Atwell, analyst at Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co., expects Alcoa to report $1.42 before the charge, Alcan
to report 36 cents (before the gain), and Reynolds to report
$1.84.
   But economic difficulties continued to roll right off the
backs of the nation's copper companies. Prices averaged about
$1.18 a pound for the quarter, up from $1.14 a year ago and
well above what analysts had expected for the end of the
year. John Gross of J.E. Gross &amp; Associates had predicted
copper would end the year at $1 a pound. "This bull market
has persisted far, far longer than anybody expected," he
said.
   In trying to explain the apparent strength in the copper
market, analysts have pointed to stronger economies overseas,
especially Asia and, until recently, Europe. "This is not a
domestic industry," said Mr. Atwell, adding that the U.S.
makes up a smaller part of the world's economy than it used
to. Other analysts suggest that copper-consuming companies
have been keeping higher inventories of copper because they
fear supplies could be disrupted in politically unstable
countries, such as Peru and Chile.
   Many analysts predict that copper prices will fall in
1991; Peter Ingersoll at Shearson is estimating a 95 cent
average price for the year, compared with $1.19 in 1990.
Besides the slowing economy, the December start of operations
at Escondida, a large copper mine in Chile, is expected to
add 250,000 tons of copper to world supplies this year.
   But Kenneth Friedman, analyst at Boettcher &amp; Co., Denver,
thinks the prices are strong because of larger, more longterm
structural changes that turned a chronic oversupply of copper
into a chronic undersupply. "For better than 10 years, copper
pricing was so poor that no additions were made to world-wide
capacity," said Mr. Friedman. "Demand finally caught up with
and surpassed capacity. He is predicting prices will rise in
the first quarter of 1991.
   For the present, strong copper prices are expected to have
boosted fourth-quarter earnings of copper companies modestly.
Mr. Ingersoll at Shearson estimates Magma Copper Co. earnings
will be 52 cents compared with 14 cents a year ago and Phelps
Dodge Corp. will report $3 a share compared with $2.76 a
share a year earlier before a $375 million charge for the
writedown of assets. Because of a charge of $1.24 a share for
environmental cleanups, Mr. Ingersoll expects Asarco Inc. to
report earnings of five cents compared with $1.42 a year ago.
   Goldman's Mr. Atwell puts Asarco at about $1.35 before the
charge and Phelps Dodge at $3.16. He estimates Cyprus
Minerals Co. will report operating earnings of 83 cents
compared with 84 cents. Cyprus announced it will take a
charge of about $40 million, after taxes, to write down its
Tonapah, Nev., molybdenum mine assets.
   For gold, the average price for the quarter dipped 2.6% to
$381 an ounce from $391, according to J.E. Gross, reversing
the price increase that came in the third quarter as a result
of Mideast worries. Some companies made up for the difference
by increasing production, but operating problems plagued
others.
   John Phizackerley at Shearson said he expects American
Barrick Resources Corp. to report earnings of 11 cents
compared with 10 cents a year ago, Battle Mountain Gold
Corp., seven cents compared with eight cents, Homestake
Mining Corp., two cents compared with operating earnings of
five cents, and Newmont Gold Corp., 38 cents, about the same
as last year. He expects Echo Bay to report operating income
of about eight cents a share compared with an operating
profit of nine cents a share a year ago. The company is
expected to take a charge of 32 cents a share for the fourth
quarter to write down its assets of the Alta Bay joint
venture, a group of mines in Nevada. In the 1989 fourth
quarter, the company took a writedown of $20 million, or 20
cents a share, for an investment in some Canadian companies,
which resulted in a net loss of 11 cents a share for the
period.
   Coal companies have finally solved many of the operating
and labor problems that have plagued them over the past year,
analysts said. Companies reported no major disruptions in
contract shipments, but the buildup of utility company
stockpiles through the year caused the spot market price to
decline.
   In spite of dismal earnings by its precious metals
division, coal producer Nerco Inc. should report profit of 58
cents a share for the quarter compared with 60 cents for the
year-ago period, estimates Marc Cohen, analyst at Kidder
Peabody &amp; Co. He also predicts Pittston Co. will report net
of 40 cents a share compared with a year-ago loss of seven
cents a share. The company was experiencing the adverse
effects of the coal miners' strike in the year-ago period,
but "even without a strike, this is a good comparison," Mr.
Cohen said. Pittston is beginning to enjoy better
productivity at its mines, he said. Westmoreland Coal Co.
will report net of 18 cents to 20 cents for the quarter
compared with 36 cents in the year-ago period, Mr. Cohen
predicts. A couple of short work stoppages affected earnings,
even though shipments continued on time.
   For 1991, Mr. Cohen expects coal industry performance to
be flat, except for those companies that start reaping the
benefits of new equipment that will raise productivity. Some
companies with low-sulfur coal reserves may begin to garner
higher contract prices by the end of the year as a result of
the acid rain provisions of the clean air law passed in 1990.
</TEXT>
