<HL>
   There's Gold Buried Under Capitol Hill
   ----
   By Jonathan Dushoff
</HL>
<DATE>
01/16/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   ABX T.ABX PD AU
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED MINING (MNG)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
INTERIOR DEPARTMENT (INR)
</GV>
<LP>
   An act passed by Congress in 1872 allows the giveaway each
year of billions of dollars in taxpayer-owned minerals and
land. The Mining Law of 1872 gives miners who discover
valuable mineral deposits on more than 300 million acres of
public land the right to develop the deposit, to extract
minerals without paying a royalty and to purchase the land
for at most $5 an acre.
   The Mining Act came from the same mold as the Homestead
Act, railroad grants and other policies aimed at settling the
West. Unlike those other giveaway policies, however, the
Mining Act is still widely applied, permitting companies to
buy valuable land at fire-sale prices: In September 1981,
Stocks Mill and Supply Co. purchased two sand and gravel
properties outside Las Vegas from the federal government for
$1,124. A government appraiser later assessed the market
value of the properties at more than $2 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A claimant must prove the existence of a valuable mineral
deposit in order to purchase land under the Mining Act, but
once the land is purchased there is no obligation to mine.
Mining claims have been used for a golf course near Phoenix
and ski areas and private residences in Western states.
   Even more egregious than the giveaway of lands, however,
is the giveaway of minerals. The U.S. collects no royalties
from the mining on most public lands of minerals covered by
the 1872 act, including gold, silver, copper, molybdenum and
uranium. The government doesn't even know how much it is
giving away, but our group has estimated that the gross value
of minerals removed under the 1872 act to be more than $4
billion a year.
   The Goldstrike mine in Nevada is the largest known gold
deposit in the country, with a gross value of roughly $6
billion. The taxpayers own both the land and the gold, but
the deposit belongs to American Barrick Resources, a
Canadian-controlled company. Barrick is free to mine the gold
without royalty or, if it chooses, to purchase the land for
$5 an acre.
   The Morenci copper mine in Arizona is located on land that
was purchased by Phelps Dodge for $5 an acre under the 1872
act 50 years ago. In 1989, Phelps Dodge mined more than $500
million in copper from Morenci. The mine still has an
estimated $10 billion in reserves.
   The Sleeper mine in Nevada is one of the lowest-cost major
gold mines in the world. It is entirely owned by the people
of the U.S. but completely controlled by Amax Gold. In 1989,
Amax extracted more than $100 million in gold, and made a
profit of $64 million, even after allowing for depreciation
and depletion.
   The 1872 act removes control of public land from the hands
of the public. The holder of a valid claim has an absolute
right to mine: The Mining Act grants no discretion to the
Bureau of Land Management or the Forest Service to refuse
permission to mine.
   Federal land managers have been forced to allow uranium
mining by several companies, the largest being Energy Fuels
Nuclear, on the border of Grand Canyon National Park; pumice
mining by Copar above the wild and scenic Jemez River in New
Mexico; and mining by California Nickel Co. above the Smith
River in California. CooSand purchased an environmentally
sensitive area in the Oregon Dunes National Recreation Area
last year in order to mine sand. Mining companies may sue the
Forest Service or the Bureau of Land Management when they
feel that rules and regulations instituted to protect other
resources -- such as timber, watersheds, wildlife or scenic
values -- interfere with the right to mine.
   The public lands are held by the federal government as a
trust; they are to be managed in the best interests of the
people of the U.S. The 1872 Mining Act stands as a major
obstacle to this philosophy. There have been efforts in
Congress to reform the act for more than 100 years and these
efforts continue. It is important that reform be quick and
thorough.
   ---
   Mr. Dushoff is a policy analyst for Ralph Nader's Taxpayer
Assets Project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

